:::summary
Gaius Julius Caesar (100–44 BC) was a Roman general, statesman, and writer whose military genius and political ambition transformed the Roman Republic into what would become the Roman Empire. His campaigns, his crossing of the Rubicon, and his assassination on the Ides of March rank among the most dramatic events in ancient history. Caesar's life and legacy shaped Western civilization and provided the world into which Jesus Christ was born.
:::

